<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="535" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="535">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="535">
Body length 2.95-4.35 mm. Dorsal aspect of body with distinct colour pattern; body outline discontinuous with distinct angle between pronotum and elytra; elytral surface strongly bicarinate; elytral epipleuron broad, base of epipleuron not delimited by a transverse carina; metacoxal lines raised, with region between them deeply foveate; abdomen tectiform, basally in the middle (close to metatrochanters) with wide depression; basal ventrites with a variable number of wide 
<normalizedToken originalValue="‘macropunctures’">'macropunctures'</normalizedToken>
(
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1076/aqin.25.2.125.14038" author="Bistroem, O" journalOrPublisher="Aquatic Insects" pageId="0" pageNumber="535" pagination="125 - 155" refId="B9" refString="Bistroem, O, Nilsson, AN, 2003. Taxonomic revision and cladistic analysis of the genus Peschetius Guignot (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae). Aquatic Insects 25: 125 - 155, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1076/aqin.25.2.125.14038" title="Taxonomic revision and cladistic analysis of the genus Peschetius Guignot (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1076/aqin.25.2.125.14038" volume="25" year="2003">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Biström">Bistroem</normalizedToken>
and Nilsson 2003
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1163/187631206788838617" author="Miller, KB" journalOrPublisher="Insect Systematics and Evolution" pageId="0" pageNumber="535" pagination="257 - 279" refId="B41" refString="Miller, KB, Wolfe, GW, Bistroem, O, 2006. The phylogeny of the Hydroporinae and classification of the genus Peschetius Guignot, 1942 (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae). Insect Systematics and Evolution 37: 257 - 279, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1163/187631206788838617" title="The phylogeny of the Hydroporinae and classification of the genus Peschetius Guignot, 1942 (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.1163/187631206788838617" volume="37" year="2006">Miller et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). The species under this genus are externally rather homogeneous but the shape of the prosternal process and male genitalia are diagnostic (Bistrӧm and Nilsson 2003).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
